          "body": "Verse 18 is arguably the chapter's most theologically dense proverb and certainly its most misquoted: 'Where there is no vision, the people are unrestrained, but happy is he who keeps the law.' The word chazon is prophetic revelation — the specific disclosure God gave through His appointed seers. It is not aspirational vision, organizational vision, or personal goals. The proverb identifies prophetic revelation as the social anchor that keeps communities morally ordered. When the word of God through His spokesmen is absent — through judgment, through apostasy, through failure to listen — people cast off restraint (para, to let go, to loosen). The canonical backdrop is 1 Samuel 3:1 ('word of the LORD was rare in those days; visions were infrequent') — which introduces the moral chaos of the judges era. The positive half of the verse is equally important: 'happy is he who keeps the torah.' The individual who internalizes and obeys God's revealed law retains the blessing that the vision-less society is forfeiting. This is Psalm 1 in proverbial compression — the man who meditates on the law is blessed while the wicked are like chaff. Verse 18 connects the social (chazon absent → community unrestrained) and the individual (torah kept → individual blessed) into a single moral ecology."
