    "intro": "Interpretation moves from what the text says to what it means — tracing the author's argument, its canonical resonances, and its historical context. The Hezekiah scribes who compiled Proverbs 29 were not randomly collecting aphorisms; they were giving Judah a comprehensive wisdom catechism for covenant life. The movements below trace the chapter's argument across its major domains: personal accountability, political theology, domestic discipline, prophetic revelation, and the governing antithesis between fear of man and trust in the LORD.",
