        "excerpt": "A man who hardens his neck after much reproof will suddenly be broken beyond remedy.",
        "body": "Proverbs 29:1 opens the chapter as a threshold verse — a warning that the rest of the chapter's wisdom is only useful if the reader has not yet crossed into the irreversible hardness it describes. The Hebrew anatomical image is precise: a stiff-necked animal cannot be guided or corrected; it must be broken or destroyed. The neck is the seat of submission; hardening it is the bodily posture of defiance against authority.\n\nThree elements of the proverb demand exegetical attention. The word 'after much reproof' (merab tokhechah) indicates a pattern, not an episode. The shattering is not the consequence of ignoring one warning; it is the consequence of a life-pattern of ignoring warnings. This is what makes the proverb so unnerving: by the time the breaking comes, the man has had every opportunity to avoid it. The tragedy is not that he was never warned but that he was warned repeatedly.\n\nThe adverb 'suddenly' (peta) appears elsewhere in Proverbs as the signature of catastrophe that overtakes the complacent (3:25; 6:15; 24:22). The wicked and the fool do not see their ruin approaching because they have trained themselves not to look. The suddenness is not divine cruelty; it is the harvest of a long-cultivated blindness. The shattering comes when the man is still not expecting it.\n\nThe phrase 'beyond remedy' (ein marpe) seals the proverb with finality. Marpe (healing, cure, medicine) is one of Proverbs' key words for restoration — it appears in 12:18; 13:17; 15:4; 16:24. Its negation here is absolute: no healing remains. This is the theological backdrop for the rest of the chapter's appeal — Proverbs 29 is calling on those who have not yet hardened irreversibly to receive the wisdom being offered, before peta arrives.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Qashah* (hardens, stiffens) is the verb God uses of Pharaoh's heart in Exodus 7:3 — the connection is canonical. *Marpe* (remedy, healing) is used of the tongue's healing power in 12:18 and 15:4; its absence here is the negation of wisdom's greatest gift. *Peta* (suddenly) appears in Proverbs 6:15 of the wicked man's destruction — the same adverb, the same suddenness."
