        "excerpt": "When the righteous increase, the people rejoice, but when a wicked man rules, people groan... If a king judges the poor with truth, his throne will be established forever.",
        "body": "Proverbs 29 contains the most concentrated political theology in the Hezekiah collection. Five proverbs address the king or ruler directly, and their cumulative message is coherent: the moral character of leadership is the determinative variable for communal well-being. This is not merely a pragmatic observation; it is a theological claim grounded in Israel's covenant understanding of kingship.\n\nVerse 2 frames the entire argument sociologically. The verb translated 'increase' (ravah) signals not merely numerical growth but the rise to civic influence — when righteousness is amplified in a community's leadership and influence structures, the people rejoice (samach). The opposite is equally stark: when a wicked man rules, the people groan (anach — to sigh, to mourn, the language of oppressed labor in Exodus 2:23-24). The wording is corporate: 'the people' as a social body either flourish or suffer together based on who governs them.\n\nVerse 4 specifies the mechanism. The king who exercises mishpat (justice, the right ordering of social relationships according to divine standard) brings stability to the land (amad — to cause to stand, to establish). The bribe-taker overthrows (haras — to tear down, to demolish) it. The king's justice is architecturally constructive; his corruption is architecturally destructive. The metaphor of building and demolishing is not accidental — the Deuteronomic covenant had made the land itself the register of the king's faithfulness (Deuteronomy 17:14-20).\n\nVerse 12 introduces the sociological cascade: if the ruler listens to lies, all his ministers become wicked. The court's moral character is derivative of its head's receptivity to truth or falsehood. Wickedness in leadership is not contained; it is contagious downward through every institutional layer. This observation is one of the most empirically verifiable in the entire chapter.\n\nVerse 14 provides the positive counterpart and canonical grounding. The king who judges the dal (the economically thin, the vulnerable poor) with emet (truth, reliability) has his throne established forever (kun, to be firmly set, the same verb used of David's dynasty in 2 Samuel 7:12-16). The justice toward the poor is the covenant condition for dynastic permanence. Verse 26 provides the theological ceiling: true mishpat for any man comes from the LORD. The king who gives it is channeling what only God ultimately dispenses.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Mishpat* (justice, 29:4, 26) is the central term of Israel's covenant ethics — it appears over 400 times in the Hebrew Bible. *Dal* (poor, 29:7, 14) — the economically thin, literally the hanging-down one — is Proverbs' specific word for the socially vulnerable. *Kun* (established, 29:14) is the dynastic-covenant verb of 2 Samuel 7 — the connection to Davidic covenant promises is deliberate."
