        "excerpt": "The rod and reproof give wisdom, but a child who gets his own way brings shame to his mother... Correct your son, and he will give you comfort.",
        "body": "Proverbs 29 contains five proverbs touching the household and those within it (29:3, 15, 17, 19, 21). Together they form a coherent domestic theology: wisdom must be transmitted through structured correction, not indulgence, and the parent who refuses this process has not spared the child but abandoned the child to a worse outcome.\n\nVerse 3 frames the domestic stakes by pairing the son who loves wisdom with the son who keeps company with harlots. The wise son makes his father rejoice (samach); the prodigal son squanders (avad — to destroy, to cause to perish) his wealth. Wealth here is hon — the entire resource base of a household. The contrast is not merely moral but economic and relational: wisdom preserves; folly dissipates. The book of Proverbs has been making this argument since chapter 5; here in chapter 29 it appears as a simple empirical observation about what fathers observe in sons.\n\nVerses 15 and 17 form a matched pair. In verse 15, the rod and reproof together produce wisdom; the child who is released (shalach — sent away, let loose) brings shame to his mother. The Hebrew idiom of the rod is not indiscriminate violence but structured, purposeful correction — the same shevet used of the shepherd's staff in Psalm 23:4, the instrument that guides and protects. Verse 17 states the positive promise: correct your son and he will give you nuach (rest, peace) and maadan (delight) to your soul. The temporal structure is crucial — the correction is present-tense, the rest and delight are future-tense. Faithfulness now produces fruit later; indulgence now produces shame later.\n\nVerses 19 and 21 apply the same principle to the household servant and offer a warning that extends beyond the master-slave relationship to any context where authority refuses to enforce its own direction. The servant who cannot be corrected by words alone (29:19) requires action, not merely speech. The servant pampered from youth (29:21) ends as something unclassifiable — manon is a hapax legomenon whose precise meaning is debated, but the context makes the danger clear: indulgent familiarity dissolves the structures that protect both parties. Peter Davids' note on the household codes of the New Testament is instructive: the wisdom tradition consistently frames household governance as a matter of theological seriousness, not merely social convention.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shalach* (left to himself, 29:15) — to send away, to release; the word used for dismissal, even divorce. A child 'sent away' from correction is not free; he is abandoned. *Shevet* (rod, 29:15) — the shepherd's staff, the ruler's scepter, the instrument of both guidance and discipline. *Manon* (29:21) — a hapax legomenon of uncertain meaning; major translations differ (NASB 'son,' ESV 'grief,' NET 'ingratitude'). The context of indulgence → unexpected outcome is clear regardless of the precise nuance."
