        "excerpt": "The fear of man brings a snare, but he who trusts in the LORD will be exalted. Many seek the ruler's favor, but justice for man comes from the LORD.",
        "body": "Verses 25-27 form the chapter's theological climax and its irreducible conclusion. The entire survey of kings and courts, fools and wise men, disciplined children and hardened necks converges here on a single question: what is the governing orientation of your life — fear of man or trust in the LORD?\n\nVerse 25 names the problem with surgical precision. Charadah adam (the trembling-terror of man) is a moqesh — a fowler's trap, the same word used in 29:6 for the trap transgression sets for the evil man. The connection is deliberate: the man who fears other men is caught as surely as the man whose sin entangles him. Both are in traps; both are unable to move freely. The trap of man-fear is particularly insidious because it masquerades as social wisdom — attentiveness to what people think, calibration of behavior to social acceptance. But Proverbs 29 refuses that reclassification: it is a snare.\n\nThe alternative is batach — to trust, to lean on, to rest the full weight of your confidence on. The object is the LORD (Yehovah — the covenant name, the personal name of Israel's God). He who trusts in the LORD is sagav — set securely on high, placed in an inaccessible position of safety, like a mountain fortification beyond the reach of the enemy (cf. Psalm 59:1; Psalm 91:14). The spatial image is of elevation beyond the reach of the social pressures that trapped the man-fearer. Verse 26 provides the theological rationale: many seek the ruler's face (paneh — the turned-toward countenance, a symbol of favor and access), but man's mishpat (justice, righteous outcome) comes from the LORD. The ruler cannot give what only God dispenses. Seeking his face for ultimate security is seeking in the wrong place.\n\nVerse 27 closes the chapter with the most absolute statement in the collection. Toevah (abomination) is deployed twice, symmetrically: the unjust man is toevah to the tsaddiq; the yashar (upright) man is toevah to the rasha. The symmetry is remarkable — the incompatibility runs in both directions with equal force. This is not the righteous man's emotional discomfort with the wicked; it is a structural, moral, irreducible incompatibility. The chapter that began with one man's hardened neck ends with the declaration that two entire ways of life are mutually and permanently repulsive. The reader cannot finish Proverbs 29 without deciding which abomination he is willing to be.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Charadah* (fear, terror) — intense trembling dread; used of the trembling of armies before battle (1 Samuel 14:15) and of Israel at Sinai (Exodus 19:16). *Batach* (trust) — the Psalms' primary word for covenant reliance; to lean full weight upon. *Sagav* (set securely on high) — a military metaphor for inaccessible elevation; related to misgav (stronghold, refuge) of the Psalms. *Toevah* (abomination) — the strongest Hebrew word for moral incompatibility; Levitical purity language applied here to the two-ways conclusion."
